place.name: Huset
nice.name: Huset
place.text: Built in 1877 this was the town’s main museum for almost 100 years, showing both art, natural history exhibits, and prehistoric artefacts. All of these collections have since grown out of the space and have been given their own separate museums. In 1972 the building was briefly illegally occupied by squatters and then turned in to a community house. Known simply as "The House" it offered public facilities for arts and crafts (such as woodworking  and pottery workshops). Most of the ground floor was converted into an amazing indoor playground, delighting children all though the 80s and 90s. It now houses several music venues.
xtraimgtxt: Some of the indoor playground interior has been moved to Legeland Langenæsstien.

place.name: Unikollegier
nice.name: Park Kollegierne
place.text: The “Park Dorms” are among the most popular student housing in the city. Most students at Aarhus University live off campus, but a lucky few get to live here in the middle of the university park. Among the lucky were Queen Margrethe II, who lived here in the early 1960s when she studied archaeology and political science. Towards the end of WWII, the British Royal Air Force bombed these buildings, leaving the rest of Aarhus nearly untouched. This was not because of any issues with the students, but because the German occupation forces had commandeered the buildings and were using them as headquarters for the Gestapo.
xtraimgtxt: Crown princess Margrethe brewing tea in the shared kitchen at park kollegierne, 1961.
